Data package

Here youâ€™ll need a number of data that I have developped for vietnam. To install them, you need the package remote installed on your system:

> install.packages("remote")

Then install the following packages:

> remotes::install_github("epix-project/gdpm")
> remotes::install_github("epix-project/gadmVN")
> remotes::install_github("epix-project/gso")

> library(gdpm)

If you want hepatitis:

> hepatitis <- getid(hepatitis)

which gives:

> head(hepatitis)
     province    month year incidence_hepatitis mortality_hepatitis
5293 An Giang  January 1980                  NA                  NA
5297 An Giang February 1980                  NA                  NA
5298 An Giang    March 1980                  NA                  NA
5299 An Giang    April 1980                  NA                  NA
5300 An Giang      May 1980                  NA                  NA
5301 An Giang     June 1980                  NA                  NA

You can see the time range:

> range(hepatitis$year)
[1] 1980 2017

You can also see the number of provinces:

> length(unique(hepatitis$province))
[1] 39

39 is the number of provinces that existed in Vietnam in 1980. These provinces have split since then to reach a number of 63 in 2008. For consistency, we always use the provincesâ€™ definition of the earlier time in the data. For example, if you are interested in the hepatitis data since 2008 instead of 1980:

> hepatitis2 <- getid(hepatitis, from = 2008)

You can see that, for this time range:

> range(hepatitis2$year)
[1] 2008 2017

you know have the 63 provinces that you could expect:

> length(unique(hepatitis2$province))
[1] 63

Maps of Vietnamese provinces

For handling maps in R, you need the following package:

> library(sf)
Linking to GEOS 3.6.1, GDAL 2.1.3, PROJ 4.9.3

Maps for Vietnam from GADM are in the following package:

> library(gadmVN)

The retrieval of maps here follows the same principle as for the surveillance data: depending on the date you want, youâ€™ll get different maps. For example, if you want the map of the provinces of Vietnam in 1980:

> vietnam1980 <- gadm(1980, "provinces")

which gives:

Mapping a variable

Letâ€™s say now that you want to map the incidence in January 2008. First, you need to retrieve these values. For that, letâ€™s use this package:

Attaching package: 'dplyr'

The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union

If you want to map the incidence values, simply do

> plot(hep_map["incidence_hepatitis"])

You can twickle the look of the map. I let you look at the help of the function for that or, even better, at the vignettes of the sf package. You can also aggregate the data of several provinces or plot by region (youâ€™ll see that the regions information in available in the vietnam data frame). Let me know if there are things that you have difficulties doing.

Population data

In addition to the dplyr package, here weâ€™ll need the purrr package:

> library(purrr)

Socio-demo-economic data from GSO are available in the following package:

> library(gso)

There is a huge amount of data in this package and it may not be super easy to find what you are looking for. To make it easier, load the content data frame:

> data(content)

content is a big data frame of the metadata of the data:

It seems that the first or the third data sets could be useful for you, i.e. demography_1 and demography_5 here. To retrieve the data sets:

> demo1 <- content %>% 
+   filter(data_name == "demography_1") %>% 
+   pluck("data") %>% 
+   first() %>% 
+   transmute(year     = year,
+             province = province,
+             popsize  = 1000 * average_population_thous_pers)

which gives:

> head(demo1)
  year          province popsize
1 2011          An Giang 2149000
2 2011 Ba Ria - Vung Tau 1022500
3 2011         Bac Giang 1581800
4 2011           Bac Kan  300400
5 2011          Bac Lieu  864900
6 2011          Bac Ninh 1063400

and

> demo5 <- content %>% 
+   filter(data_name == "demography_5") %>% 
+   pluck("data") %>% 
+   first() %>% 
+   transmute(year     = year,
+             province = province,
+             popsize  = 1000 * total)

which gives:

> head(demo5)
  year          province popsize
1 1995          An Giang 1970100
2 1995 Ba Ria - Vung Tau  708900
3 1995         Bac Giang 1431000
4 1995           Bac Kan  254200
5 1995          Bac Lieu  709500
6 1995          Bac Ninh  916000

Note that the time range of the 2 data sets are not the same:

> range(demo1$year)
[1] 2011 2016

and

> range(demo5$year)
[1] 1995 2016

If you are interested in the population sizes in 2011:

> demo1_2011 <- demo1 %>%
+   filter(year == 2011) %>% 
+   select(-year) %>% 
+   arrange(province)

and

> demo5_2011 <- demo5 %>%
+   filter(year == 2011) %>% 
+   select(-year) %>% 
+   na.exclude() %>% # removing Ha Tay
+   arrange(province)

You can verify that the 2 data sets are actually identical:

> all(unlist(map2(demo1_2011, demo5_2011, identical)))
[1] TRUE

You can also check the total population size:

> sum(demo1_2011$popsize)
[1] 87859700

Same as before, the province names in the gso package are compatible with those in the gdpm and the gadmVN packages, which makes it easy for you to map the data:

> pop_map <- left_join(vietnam, demo1_2011, by = "province")

and:

> plot(pop_map["popsize"])

or to calculate incidence rates, per 100,000 for example:

> incidence_rate_map <- vietnam %>% 
+   left_join(hep, by = "province") %>% 
+   left_join(demo1_2011, by = "province") %>% 
+   mutate(incidence_rate = 1e5 * incidence_hepatitis / popsize)

and plot it:

> plot(incidence_rate_map["incidence_rate"])
